Prologue
"Please!", the queen Eirwen pleaded. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The King of Ice looked at his wife from the top of his throne, his royal advisor beside him. She had given birth to a daughter. He scowled at the thought.
The little girl looked a lot like her mother: pale blue eyes, white hair with blue streaks. The King of Ice thought a daughter would make him look weak. After all, he had only had sons up until then.
"Your only options are to kill your child or send her back into nature. That's her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat her name as if it were a poison. He did it every time.
Frostwell had not always been a single kingdom. It had been split in two, the North and the South. In the north, a non-magical kingdom. In the south, a kingdom filled with fantastical representations of power. Due to the greed of the North, the two kingdoms had torn each other apart in an endless war, until the South proposed a truce.
The South was cornered, and its royal family would have done anything to stop the bloodshed. They proposed that their only princess become the queen of the North and bear a son destined to be the future king. Then, the South would have allied itself with the North to form a single kingdom. The North had accepted, and Princess Eirwen had married Prince Akull.
"I beg of you, my lady, in exchange for the life of my child, do whatever you want with me, imprison me, banish me, or even kill me," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child tightly in her arms.
The King of Ice lowered his gaze at his wife, disgust in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he would have pity on her. The one with whom he had lived for twenty-two years, who had always taken care of him in his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"Alright, the child will be allowed to live in the palace," he began, extracting a sigh of relief from his wife. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
The advisor and Queen Eirwen herself shared a horrified glance. She slowly lowered her gaze. "Yes, My Lady," she said, bowing.
The King of Ice ordered his royal advisor to take the child to one of Eirwen's vacant apartments. Once that was done, he had the guards escort Eirwen to the execution site, where all the townspeople could witness the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, the townspeople cried out in indignation at seeing their only queen, the kindest one, about to be killed. Some people were crying, others were shouting and trying to attack the guards, while others were still wondering what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the most feared person in the kingdom made their entrance. The fire user. Former Queen Eirwen was going to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. This was the cruelest punishment in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostwell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the fire user set the gallows on fire, and only one tear rolled down the cheek of the former queen.
"Survive, Kari". This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the corridors
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds coming from the farthest room to the left in the south wing of the still-frozen palace. The aides passing by would always wonder what was inside that room, frightened by what could be inside. The servants' rumors danced in the corridors. It was thought that the king of Ice's wife, Eirwen, was in that room, waiting to be released.
"They couldn't be more wrong," thought Ivory as she walked towards the south wing, while the aides came and went murmuring to each other. They have no idea what's inside that room.
Of course, these rumors also applied to Kari, as Kari was the only person authorized to enter the room.
Tap, tap. "Miss Kari, are you there?" Ivory whispered at the beautifully decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Kari wondered if she would invite her in, unlike the other times when Kari had asked her to enter. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory chuckled at the memory. Kari had thrown a book on her shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
There was only one knock from inside, which seemed to mean she was there, but after all, where else could she be?
"Can I enter?" Ivory asked, remembering the time when Kari had let her in without asking permission.
A knock came from inside. It seemed to mean yes. Ivory shivered, from the cold, but also from the noise. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from a room that was supposed to be empty, even though she had entered this room for years.
"Here I am," said Ivory, opening the door slowly. The scene inside the room was unusual, by normal standards, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and a multitude of ice statues were scattered around. The room had no windows and almost no light. It was also colder than the rest of the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have hit inside.
The girl who was there was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her blankets, reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern lit up the space.
"Which notebook is it?" asked Ivory as she sat down next to Kari on her bed.
